                'content'      => "It has been one year since SpaceX completed its first fully commercial human spaceflight mission with paying customers, and the space tourism industry is growing faster than almost anyone predicted. Over the past twelve months, six different companies have conducted crewed suborbital and orbital flights, carrying a combined total of 47 civilians to space.\n\nThe price of a suborbital experience — a 10-minute flight that takes passengers above the Kármán line and provides several minutes of weightlessness — has dropped to around \$250,000, down from \$450,000 at the start of 2025. Blue Origin's New Shepard vehicle has proved the most reliable, completing 23 consecutive successful missions.\n\nOrbital experiences remain far more expensive, with prices starting at \$10 million for a Crew Dragon seat. However, SpaceX has announced plans for a dedicated space hotel partnership that aims to bring orbital tourism within reach of high-net-worth individuals rather than exclusively billionaires.\n\nA small but growing number of Asian tourists have been among the passengers. Japan, South Korea, and China have all seen their citizens fly commercially. Indonesia has not yet been represented, though a consortium of Indonesian investors is reportedly in discussions with one provider about a dedicated Indonesian mission.\n\nCritics of the industry argue that the environmental cost of rocket launches — each of which releases significant quantities of black carbon into the upper atmosphere — is unjustifiable given the climate crisis. Defenders counter that the technology being developed will eventually have transformative benefits for humanity.",
                'image_url'    => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/space/800/400',
                'category_id'  => 1,
                'author'       => 'Chris Northen',
                'views'        => 7500,
                'published_at' => '2026-04-29 12:00:00',
