                'id'           => 19,
                'title'        => 'Indonesia Wins First Olympic Gold in Athletics',
                'slug'         => 'indonesia-first-olympic-gold-athletics',
                'excerpt'      => 'History made at the 2026 Asian Athletics Championship in Surabaya.',
                'content'      => "In a moment that will be replayed on Indonesian television for decades, sprinter Lalu Muhammad Zohri crossed the finish line of the 100-meter final at the Asian Athletics Championship in Surabaya to take gold — setting a new Asian record of 9.81 seconds in the process. The crowd of 40,000 at Gelora Delta Sidoarjo erupted in scenes of pure joy.\n\nZohri, who first captured national attention as a teenager with his World Junior Championship title, has spent the past four years under a specialist sprint coach in the United States. The investment in elite-level foreign coaching has clearly paid dividends, with the 25-year-old now comfortably among the top 10 sprinters in the world.\n\n\"I ran for every Indonesian today,\" Zohri said through tears at the post-race ceremony. \"Every child who watches this and thinks they can be a champion — I want them to know they can.\"\n\nThe achievement comes at a significant moment for Indonesian athletics. The country is preparing to host a major multi-sport event in 2028 and has been under pressure to develop elite athletic programs rather than relying on the traditional strengths of badminton and weightlifting.\n\nThe Indonesian Ministry of Youth and Sport has announced that a new high-performance athletics training center will be constructed in East Java, with a target of producing five internationally competitive sprinters within a decade.",
