                'title'        => 'Women\'s World Cup: Host Nation Indonesia Makes History',
                'slug'         => 'womens-world-cup-indonesia-history',
                'excerpt'      => 'Indonesia\'s women\'s team qualifies for the knockout stage for the first time.',
                'content'      => "The Indonesian women's national football team has achieved the unthinkable, becoming the first host nation in the history of the Women's World Cup to qualify for the knockout stage on debut. A hard-fought 1-0 victory over Denmark in their final group stage match, secured by a stunning 87th-minute header from captain Siti Rahayu, confirmed Indonesia's place in the Round of 16.\n\nThe result was met with scenes of extraordinary jubilation across the archipelago. In Jakarta alone, an estimated 150,000 people gathered in public spaces to watch the final minutes of the match on giant screens, with the country coming to a virtual standstill during the final 15 minutes.\n\nThe team's success has been built over four years of intensive development following Indonesia's successful bid to host the tournament. The Football Association of Indonesia partnered with the Dutch FA to provide coaching expertise, and 23 of the 26-woman squad now play professionally in Europe or Australia.\n\n\"When we were given this opportunity to host the World Cup, we made a promise that the Indonesian team would make their country proud,\" said coach Vera Pauw. \"These players have worked harder than any group I have ever worked with. They deserve every moment of what they're experiencing.\"\n\nIndonesia will face Spain in the Round of 16, a match that will be played on Thursday at Gelora Bung Karno in Jakarta. Ticket demand has been overwhelming, with the stadium's 77,000-capacity expected to sell out within minutes when additional allocation is released tomorrow.",
