                'title'        => 'Ocean Plastics: New Biodegradable Alternative Passes Final Tests',
                'slug'         => 'biodegradable-plastic-ocean-solution',
                'excerpt'      => 'Scientists develop a fully marine-degradable plastic replacement.',
                'content'      => "A research consortium led by scientists at the Bandung Institute of Technology and Stanford University has successfully completed field trials of a novel biopolymer material that degrades completely in seawater within six months without releasing microplastics or toxic compounds. The material, derived from seaweed and cassava starch, can be manufactured at roughly 1.5 times the cost of conventional single-use plastic — a premium that packaging industry analysts say will fall below parity within three years as production scales.\n\nThe Indonesian researchers played a central role in developing the material, motivated by Indonesia's status as the world's second-largest contributor to ocean plastic pollution. The Jawa Sea and Makassar Strait are among the most plastic-contaminated waterways globally, with significant damage to coral reefs and fisheries.\n\n\"We have a responsibility because of our geography and our history with plastic waste, but we also have incredible natural resources — our seaweed industry is the world's second largest — that give us an advantage in developing solutions,\" said the project's principal investigator, Professor Andi Kurniawan.\n\nSeveral Indonesian consumer goods companies have already signed letters of intent to pilot the material in their packaging lines. The government has introduced a regulatory fast track for sustainable packaging innovations, allowing compliant products to bypass certain import and safety approval timelines.\n\nEnvironmentalists have cautiously welcomed the development but note that even biodegradable materials are inferior to reduced consumption and robust waste management systems. \"This is a useful tool, not a silver bullet,\" said a spokesperson for the Coral Triangle Initiative.",
