                'id'           => 25,
                'title'        => 'Renewable Energy Hits 40% of Indonesia Power Grid',
                'slug'         => 'renewable-energy-40-percent-indonesia',
                'excerpt'      => 'Next-generation solar and geothermal plants power a greener future.',
                'content'      => "Indonesia has achieved a major milestone in its energy transition, with renewable sources now accounting for 40% of total electricity generation capacity — a figure that exceeded the government's original 2026 target of 34%. The achievement reflects accelerating investment in geothermal, solar, and hydroelectric generation over the past four years.\n\nGeothermal energy, for which Indonesia has the world's largest resource potential, continues to be the cornerstone of the transition. Seven new geothermal plants came online in 2025 across Java, Sulawesi, and North Sumatra, adding 1,200 megawatts of reliable baseload capacity. Unlike solar and wind, geothermal provides 24-hour generation that does not require battery storage.\n\nSolar installations have also surged, with the cost of utility-scale solar in Indonesia falling to \$0.028 per kilowatt-hour — comparable to the cheapest coal generation. A cluster of large solar parks in the arid regions of East Nusa Tenggara and East Java are expected to add 3,500 MW of capacity by end of year.\n\nThe state electricity company PLN has invested heavily in grid modernization to handle the variability of renewable generation, including advanced energy management systems and expanded interconnection between islands. Battery storage installations are growing rapidly, though the high capital cost remains a constraint.\n\nThe transition has created over 180,000 jobs in renewable energy construction, manufacturing, and operations — partially offsetting the decline in coal-related employment in regions like South Kalimantan and East Kalimantan.",
