                'title'        => 'Political Reform Bill Passes Despite Opposition',
                'slug'         => 'political-reform-bill-passes',
                'excerpt'      => 'Parliament approves sweeping changes to campaign finance laws.',
                'content'      => "Indonesia's parliament voted 362 to 199 to pass the most significant campaign finance reform in the country's democratic history, introducing strict limits on political donations, mandatory real-time disclosure of campaign expenditure, and a new independent electoral audit body with prosecutorial powers.\n\nThe bill, which had been the subject of intense lobbying from both business groups and civil society organizations, passed after a marathon 14-hour parliamentary session that extended into the early hours of the morning. Thirteen members of the ruling coalition crossed the floor to vote with the opposition in support of the reforms.\n\nKey provisions include a cap on individual donations to political parties of Rp 500 million per year, a ban on corporate donations above Rp 2 billion, and a requirement for all campaign expenditure above Rp 10 million to be reported to the new audit body within 48 hours. Violations carry penalties of up to 10 years imprisonment.\n\nTransparency International Indonesia hailed the vote as \"a watershed moment,\" while noting that the true test will be in enforcement. Previous campaign finance regulations have been largely ignored due to weak oversight mechanisms.\n\nThe opposition, which supports the reforms in principle, voted against several procedural aspects of the bill's passage, arguing that insufficient time was provided for public consultation. They have indicated they will challenge specific provisions in the Constitutional Court.",
