                'id'           => 28,
                'title'        => 'Nutritional Science Upends Decades of Dietary Advice',
                'slug'         => 'nutritional-science-new-findings',
                'excerpt'      => 'New findings challenge long-held beliefs about fat, carbs, and protein.',
                'content'      => "A series of landmark studies published simultaneously in three leading medical journals has overturned several widely held beliefs about dietary fat, carbohydrates, and their relationship to cardiovascular disease and metabolic health. The research represents the culmination of a decade of large-scale, rigorously controlled nutritional epidemiology.\n\nPerhaps most controversially, the studies found that dietary saturated fat — long demonized as the primary driver of heart disease — has a more nuanced relationship with cardiovascular outcomes than previously understood. The risk associated with saturated fat appears to depend heavily on the food matrix in which it is consumed and on what replaces it in the diet. Replacing saturated fat with refined carbohydrates, as public health campaigns encouraged in the 1980s and 1990s, appears to have been actively harmful.\n\nThe research also significantly rehabilitates the role of dietary fat in metabolic health. Participants following a diet rich in whole-food fats — avocado, nuts, olive oil, and fatty fish — showed better insulin sensitivity, lower triglycerides, and smaller waist circumference than those following low-fat dietary guidelines.\n\n\"We are not saying fat is fine and carbs are the enemy,\" said the coordinating researcher. \"We are saying that quality matters more than macronutrient ratios, and that decades of focusing on single nutrients rather than whole dietary patterns has led us astray.\"\n\nIndonesian nutritionists have welcomed the findings, noting that traditional Indonesian diets — rich in tempeh, fish, vegetables, and coconut — appear vindicated by the new evidence, and that the country's shift toward ultra-processed Western food imports is the real nutritional concern.",
