                'title'        => 'Global Cybercrime Treaty Signed by 130 Nations',
                'slug'         => 'global-cybercrime-treaty-130-nations',
                'excerpt'      => 'Historic agreement creates a framework for cross-border cybercrime prosecution.',
                'content'      => "Representatives from 130 countries signed the United Nations Convention against Cybercrime in Vienna, creating for the first time a binding international legal framework for investigating and prosecuting cybercriminal activity that crosses national borders. The treaty, which took six years to negotiate, will enter into force once ratified by 40 signatory states.\n\nThe convention establishes common definitions for cybercrime offenses including unauthorized access, data theft, ransomware, and child sexual exploitation material online. It creates mutual legal assistance obligations, allowing countries to request evidence and cooperation from fellow signatories without going through slow diplomatic channels.\n\nHuman rights organizations have raised concerns about several provisions that they say could be used by authoritarian governments to prosecute legitimate political dissent and investigative journalism conducted online. The convention's definition of cybercrime is broad enough to potentially criminalize activities that are legal or protected under international human rights law in many countries.\n\nIndonesia signed the treaty and has committed to ratifying it within 18 months. The Ministry of Communication and Information Technology has noted that the framework will help Indonesian authorities pursue criminal groups that operate ransomware and fraud operations from overseas.\n\nThe convention is seen as particularly important for combating the rapidly growing problem of cyber-enabled financial fraud, which the World Bank estimates costs the global economy \$600 billion annually — a figure that has tripled in five years.",
