                'title'        => 'Indonesia Passes Comprehensive Data Privacy Law',
                'slug'         => 'indonesia-data-privacy-law-2026',
                'excerpt'      => 'New legislation gives Indonesians control over their personal data.',
                'content'      => "After three years of debate and revisions, Indonesia's Parliament has passed a comprehensive Personal Data Protection Law that gives citizens meaningful control over how their data is collected, processed, and shared by both government agencies and private companies. The law takes effect immediately for large enterprises and will apply to all organizations within 24 months.\n\nThe legislation, widely compared to Europe's GDPR in scope and intent, requires organizations to obtain explicit consent before collecting personal data, to disclose what data is held and why, to allow individuals to access and delete their data, and to report data breaches to authorities and affected individuals within 72 hours of discovery.\n\nFines for violations can reach 2% of annual revenue for organizations that process data without adequate legal basis, and up to 4% for the most serious violations including unlawful transfer of data overseas. A new Data Protection Authority has been established with a budget of Rp 500 billion and powers to investigate, audit, and sanction.\n\nThe technology industry has broadly welcomed the regulatory clarity, noting that operating across multiple jurisdictions with inconsistent rules has been burdensome. Several multinational companies have already begun aligning their Indonesian operations with the new requirements in advance of formal enforcement.\n\nConsumer advocacy groups praised the law's passage but noted several areas where they consider the protections weaker than the European standard, including provisions allowing the government to access personal data for national security purposes without judicial oversight.",
